<HEAD>Reapportionment Changes, A Bit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The political outlook may have improved a bit
for the North in new Census population estimates.
   The South and West will wrest away some seats in the <ORGANIZATION>House of
Representatives</ORGANIZATION> after the <DATE>1990</DATE> national head count _ but maybe not
as many as had originally been thought.
   The Constitution requires seats in the <ORGANIZATION>House</ORGANIZATION> to be redistributed
among states after each census.
   The private <ORGANIZATION>Population Reference Bureau</ORGANIZATION> analyzed a complex
series of new Census estimates on <DATE>Thursday</DATE>, and predicted that 14
<ORGANIZATION>House</ORGANIZATION> seats will move from the <LOCATION>Northeast</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Midwest</LOCATION> to the South
and West after the census.
   Earlier analyses by the same group had indicated as many as 18
seats would move.
   The Census estimates include four sets of possible state
populations for <DATE>1990</DATE>, each differing slightly depending on the
amount of interstate movement by people.
   One set included no movement, and was discounted by the private
analysis group.
   But while reapportionment calculations based on the other three
varied slightly, the overall shift in seats was consistent.
   The big winner will be <LOCATION>California</LOCATION>, gaining six seats based on
the new figures. The previous calculations had called for
<LOCATION>California</LOCATION> to gain five seats.
   <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Florida</LOCATION> will gain three seats each, the new estimates
indicate. Earlier calculations had shown <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION> adding four seats
and <LOCATION>Florida</LOCATION> three.
   <LOCATION>Arizona</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Georgia</LOCATION>, which had previously been expected to gain
two seats apiece, are now expected to add one, the new study said.
   <LOCATION>Virginia</LOCATION> also will gain one, as had been expected. <LOCATION>North
Carolina</LOCATION> would add one seat under two of the estimates, but would
remain unchanged under the third.
   On the losing side, <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> is still expected to lose three
seats. <LOCATION>Pennsylvania</LOCATION>, which had been expected to drop three, now
appears likely to lose just two. <LOCATION>Ohio</LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION>Illinois</ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION>Michigan</LOCATION> will
drop two each, the same as previously expected.
   Also unchanged are losses of one seat each by <LOCATION>West Virginia</LOCATION>,
<LOCATION>Iowa</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Kansas</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Massachusetts</LOCATION>.
   <LOCATION>Wisconsin</LOCATION>, which had been expected to lose a seat, would not do
so under the new figures. And <LOCATION>Montana</LOCATION> would lose a seat under two
estimates but not under the third.
   Following the <DATE>1990</DATE> census, the <ORGANIZATION>Census Bureau</ORGANIZATION> will present the
<ORGANIZATION>White House</ORGANIZATION> with the final state population figures and the new
reapportionment numbers.
</TEXT>
