<HEAD>Democrats Bolster Redistricting Advantage</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 3rd graf to show California legislative results. Subs
14th graf to update with Washington results.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KAREN BALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrats bolstered their huge redistricting
advantage by adding two big prizes - <LOCATION>Florida</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION> - to the
list of states where they hold a lock on redrawing political lines
for the next decade.
   Besides taking the governorships in those two states -
considered key because together they stand to gain seven <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> House
seats - Democrats added <LOCATION>Rhode Island</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Oklahoma</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>New Mexico</LOCATION> to
their remapping monopolies on <DATE>Tuesday</DATE>.
   Republicans won a crucial redistricting battle by taking the
<LOCATION>California</LOCATION> governor's race. The <ORGANIZATION>GOP</ORGANIZATION> needed it to keep a role in
drawing lines for the seven new <ORGANIZATION>House</ORGANIZATION> seats <LOCATION>California</LOCATION> is expected
to gain, because Democrats easily retained control of the
<ORGANIZATION>Legislature</ORGANIZATION>.
   The <ORGANIZATION>GOP</ORGANIZATION> also scored victories by winning the <LOCATION>Ohio</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Illinois</LOCATION>
governorships, but Democrats clearly will have the national edge on
the process of reapportioning the 19 <ORGANIZATION>House</ORGANIZATION> seats that will change
hands due to population shifts of the <DATE>1980s</DATE>.
   Advantages won <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> should help cement Democrats as the <ORGANIZATION>House</ORGANIZATION>
majority party for at least another decade. Democrats also said the
<LOCATION>Florida</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION> wins would boost their <DATE>1992</DATE> presidential hopes.
   ``We feel better about the prospects of fair districts when the
pen is in Democratic hands,'' said <PERSON>Paul Tully</PERSON>, political director
for the <ORGANIZATION>Democratic National Committee</ORGANIZATION>.
   ``These are not only net victories but victories in places that
because of their population growth will grow more important to the
future of this country and also to the presidential race,'' <PERSON>Tully</PERSON>
said.
   According to preliminary <ORGANIZATION>Census Bureau</ORGANIZATION> figures, eight states
will gain and 13 will lose seats when <ORGANIZATION>House</ORGANIZATION> districts are
reapportioned next year. Democrats will control the process
outright in at least five of the states gaining <ORGANIZATION>House</ORGANIZATION> seats.
   Despite the anti-incumbent mood thought to be sweeping the
country, voters appeared unwilling to turn out their state
legislators. Millions of dollars were spent on legislative races
this year due to their importance in the redistricting picture, but
few chambers changed hands.
   The <ORGANIZATION>GOP</ORGANIZATION> turned back Democratic efforts to take over the senates
of <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Pennsylvania</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Ohio</LOCATION>. Redistricting power will be
shared in all three states, which will lose <ORGANIZATION>House</ORGANIZATION> seats in <DATE>1992</DATE>.
   ``This proves the <ORGANIZATION>Republican Party</ORGANIZATION> is alive and well despite the
doom and gloom predicted,'' said <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>'s state Senate Republican
leader, <PERSON>Ralph Marino</PERSON>.
   Democrats fended off Republican efforts to take over the state
senates in <LOCATION>Illinois</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Florida</LOCATION> and the lower chamber in
<LOCATION>Pennsylvania</LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION>GOP</ORGANIZATION> was trying to wrest control of the <ORGANIZATION>Oregon
House</ORGANIZATION> from Democrats, too.
   <LOCATION>Arizona</LOCATION>'s gubernatorial race was up for grabs, as the lead
seesawed throughout <ORGANIZATION>Election Night</ORGANIZATION>.
   Meanwhile, the <ORGANIZATION>GOP</ORGANIZATION> lost the <ORGANIZATION>Indiana House</ORGANIZATION>, but Republicans kept
control of the state <ORGANIZATION>Senate</ORGANIZATION>. Democrats captured control of the
state <ORGANIZATION>Senate</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Arizona</LOCATION>. A Democratic effort to gain control of the
<LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION> state <ORGANIZATION>Senate</ORGANIZATION> hinged on absentee ballots in two
neck-and-neck races.
   In <LOCATION>Michigan</LOCATION>, Republicans kept control of the state <ORGANIZATION>Senate</ORGANIZATION>.
   By losing in the governorships in <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Florida</LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION>GOP</ORGANIZATION>
lost its say in how political maps will be drawn for those ne
<ORGANIZATION>House</ORGANIZATION> seats.
   Similar gubernatorial wins in <LOCATION>Rhode Island</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Oklahoma</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>New
Mexico</LOCATION> gave Democrats absolute control there, too. The <ORGANIZATION>House</ORGANIZATION>
delegations in those states won't change, but Democrats can aim to
draw districts that protect their <ORGANIZATION>House</ORGANIZATION> incumbents and perhaps
endanger GOP lawmakers. The political lines for state seats are at
stake as well.
   Another victory for Democrats came in <LOCATION>Kansas</LOCATION>, where they ousted
a Republican governor and gained control of the state <ORGANIZATION>House</ORGANIZATION>. Kansas
will lose one <ORGANIZATION>House</ORGANIZATION> seat.
   Election Day began with Democrats controlling 69 of the nation's
99 legislative chambers, and that margin was on track to change
little.
   More than 6,100 legislative races were decided across the
country, but the focus of national party organizations was about 50
races in 10 states in which chambers were held by narrow
majorities.
   The Democrats were in position to draw districts that in <DATE>1992</DATE>
could pad their <ORGANIZATION>House</ORGANIZATION> majority, now at 258-175 with two vacancies,
by a dozen seats or more beyoe <DATE>Tuesday</DATE>.
   The other five <ORGANIZATION>House</ORGANIZATION> seats are expected to go to <LOCATION>Virginia</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>North
Carolina</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Georgia</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Arizona</LOCATION>. Democrats already had a
redistricting monopoly in <LOCATION>Virginia</LOCATION> and kept their sole control in
<LOCATION>North Carolina</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Georgia</LOCATION>. A nonpartisnd the gains madan commission draws
the map
in <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION>.
   Among the 13 states losing seats, <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> will suffer the most
- giving up three.
   <LOCATION>Pennsylvania</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Ohio</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Michigan</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Illinois</LOCATION> are to lose two seats
each. Losing one will be <LOCATION>Massachusetts</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>New Jersey</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>West Virginia</LOCATION>,
<LOCATION>Kentucky</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Louisiana</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Iowa</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Kansas</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Montana</LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
