Vermont and Illinois, bgng.: The Ohio</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrats on <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> padded their overwhelming
control of political redistricting, plucking the potent <LOCATION>Florida</LOCATION> and
<LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION> governorships from <ORGANIZATION>GOP</ORGANIZATION> hands and adding <LOCATION>Rhode Island</LOCATION>,
<LOCATION>Oklahoma</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>New Mexico</LOCATION> to their remapping monopolies.
   The <LOCATION>Florida</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION> defeats were disastrous for Republicans,
and Democrats were in the running for the only remaining major GOP
redistricting weapon - the <LOCATION>California</LOCATION> governorship.
   Democrats clearly will have a huge edge when lines are drawn for
<DATE>1992</DATE> congressional races, all but cementing the Republicans as the
<ORGANIZATION>House</ORGANIZATION> minority for another decade and perhaps far longer. And
Democrats were calling the <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Florida</LOCATION> victories a boost for
their <DATE>1992</DATE> presidential hopes.
   ``We feel better about the prospects of fair districts when the
pen is in Democratic hands,'' said <ORGANIZATION>Democratic National Committee</ORGANIZATION>
political director <PERSON>Paul Tully</PERSON>. ``These are not only net victories
but victories in places that because of their population growth
will grow more important to the future of this country and also to
the presidential race.''
   In all, eight states will gain and 13 will lose seats when <ORGANIZATION>House</ORGANIZATION>
districts are reapportioned to reflect population shifts of the
<DATE>1980s</DATE>, according to preliminary census data. Democrats will control
the process outright in at least five of the states gaining <ORGANIZATION>House</ORGANIZATION>
seats.
   The <LOCATION>Ohio</LOCATION> governorship was the only significant redistricting
victory for Republicans as results from gubernatorial and
legislative races trickled in. So frustrating was the <ORGANIZATION>GOP</ORGANIZATION>'s night
that the only redistricting monopoly the <ORGANIZATION>GOP</ORGANIZATION> gained was in <LOCATION>Vermont</LOCATION>
- which has only one <ORGANIZATION>House</ORGANIZATION> seat anyway.
   Despite the millions spent on oft-ignored state races with the
post-Census redistricting in mind, it appeared but a few of the
dozen targeted chambers would change hands.
   The <ORGANIZATION>GOP</ORGANIZATION> turned back Democratic efforts to take over the <LOCATION>New
York</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Pennsylvania</LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Ohio Senates</ORGANIZATION>. Redistricting power in all
three states, which will lose <ORGANIZATION>House</ORGANIZATION> seats in <DATE>1992</DATE>, will be shared.
   Republicans failed in their bid to wrest the <ORGANIZATION>Illinois Senate</ORGANIZATION>
from Democrats but won a close governor's race to keep a say in
redistricting there. The <ORGANIZATION>GOP</ORGANIZATION> was trailing in bids to win over the
<ORGANIZATION>Democratic Florida Senate</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Pennsylvania House</ORGANIZATION>. Early returns
showed control of the <ORGANIZATION>Oregon House</ORGANIZATION> within reach.
   The <ORGANIZATION>Indiana House</ORGANIZATION> was likely to go from <ORGANIZATION>GOP</ORGANIZATION> hands to the
Democrats. Other Democratic targets were the state senates in
<LOCATION>Indiana</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Michigan</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION> and both chambers in <LOCATION>Arizona</LOCATION>.
   The <ORGANIZATION>GOP</ORGANIZATION> suffered a big loss when Democrat <PERSON>Lawton Chiles</PERSON> unseated
<LOCATION>Florida</LOCATION>'s Republican governor, and things would only get worse.
   The <LOCATION>Rhode Island</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Oklahoma</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>New Mexico</LOCATION> governor's offices
went from Republican to Democratic hands and then <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION> was seized
by the Democrats too.
   Democrats now will have sole power over the remapping in those
states. <LOCATION>Florida</LOCATION> is likely to gain four <ORGANIZATION>House</ORGANIZATION> seats and <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION> three.
The <ORGANIZATION>House</ORGANIZATION> delegations in <LOCATION>Rhode Island</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Oklahoma</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>New Mexico</LOCATION>
won't change, but control of redistricting should allow Democrats
to draw districts that protect their <ORGANIZATION>House</ORGANIZATION> incumbents and perhaps
endanger GOP lawmakers.
   Another victory for Democrats came in <LOCATION>Kansas</LOCATION>, where by unseating
a Republican governor the party went from being shut out of the
process to having veto power in redistricting. Kansas will lose one
<ORGANIZATION>House</ORGANIZATION> seat.
   The Republicans' last hope was <LOCATION>California</LOCATION>, which will get seven
of the 19 shifting seats. But even with a win in the governor's
race there the <ORGANIZATION>GOP</ORGANIZATION> would only share the power with the Democratic
legislature.
   Democrats, with huge majorities in many legislative chambers,
were virtually assured a redistricting voice in all the
battleground states even before the polls opened <DATE>Tuesday</DATE>.
   The day began with Democrats controlling 69 of the nation's 99
legislative chambers and 29 of the 50 governorships.
   More than 6,100 legislative races were decided across the
country, but the focus of national party organizations was about 50
races in 10 states in which chambers are held by narrow majorities.
   Even with <LOCATION>California</LOCATION> undecided, the Democrats were in position
to draw districts that in <DATE>1992</DATE> likely would pad their majority in
the <ORGANIZATION>House</ORGANIZATION>, now at 258-175, by a dozen seats or more beyond whatever
gains they made in <DATE>Tuesday</DATE>'s elections.
   Preliminary census data suggest the remaining five <ORGANIZATION>House</ORGANIZATION> seats
that shift will go to <LOCATION>Virginia</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>North Carolina</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Georgia</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION>
and <LOCATION>Arizona</LOCATION>. Among those states, redistricting control was a
serious question only in <LOCATION>Arizona</LOCATION>. Democrats already had a
redistricting monopoly in <LOCATION>Virginia</LOCATION> and kept hold of their sole
control in <LOCATION>North Carolina</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Georgia</LOCATION>. A nonpartisan commission
draws the map in <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION>.
   Democrats were facing uphill odds in their effort to erase the
<ORGANIZATION>Arizona GOP</ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION>17-13 Senate</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>34-26 House</ORGANIZATION> majorities. But Democrat
<PERSON>Terry Goddard</PERSON> was leading in early returns in the governor's race .
If elected, he could veto any redistricting plan drawn by a
possibly Republican legislature.
   Among the 13 states losing seats, <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> will suffer the most
- giving up three.
   Gov. <PERSON>Mario Cuomo</PERSON> was headed to easy re-election and the <ORGANIZATION>New York
Assembly</ORGANIZATION> had a 92-58 Democratic majority entering <DATE>Tuesday</DATE>'s voting.
Results were slow to come in, but Democrats conceded they would not
capture the <ORGANIZATION>Senate</ORGANIZATION>, where they had hoped to wipe out a five-seat
Republican majority and gain a redistricting monopoly.
   <LOCATION>Pennsylvania</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Ohio</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Michigan</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Illinois</LOCATION> are to lose two seats
each. Losing one will be <LOCATION>Massachusetts</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>New Jersey</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>West Virginia</LOCATION>,
<LOCATION>Kentucky</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Louisiana</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Iowa</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Kansas</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Montana</LOCATION>. Democrats control
the process in <LOCATION>New Jersey</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>West Virginia</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Kentucky</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Louisiana</LOCATION>.
In <LOCATION>Massachusetts</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Iowa</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Kansas</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Montana</LOCATION> the power will be
shared.
