<HEAD>Eleven States Get Preliminary Population Reports</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   <LOCATION>Hawaii</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Nevada</LOCATION> have topped the 1-million
population mark, according to the <ORGANIZATION>Census Bureau</ORGANIZATION>, which is issuing
preliminary <DATE>1990</DATE> counts for 11 states.
   While 10 of the states showed population gains in data released
<DATE>Friday</DATE>, <LOCATION>Ohio</LOCATION> recorded a decline from the <DATE>1980</DATE> national head count.
   The bureau said that it had counted 10,777,514 people in <LOCATION>Ohio</LOCATION>,
down from 10,798,000 in <DATE>1980</DATE>.
   Officials stressed that the reports are preliminary. They are
designed to give local officials a chance to raise questions if
they find areas where they believe people have been missed or
overcounted.
   The final, official, census counts are scheduled for release on
<DATE>Dec. 31</DATE>.
   <DATE>Friday</DATE>'s report brings to 40 the number of states for which
preliminary counts have been published. The rest are expected in
the next week or two.
   Newly released state counts, and the census count in <DATE>1980</DATE> are:
   _<LOCATION>Alaska</LOCATION>, 545,774, up from 402,000.
   _<LOCATION>Arizona</LOCATION>, 3,619,064, up from 2,718,000.
   _<LOCATION>Colorado</LOCATION>, 3,272,460, up from 2,890,000.
   _<LOCATION>Hawaii</LOCATION>, 1,095,237, up from 965,000.
   _<LOCATION>Kansas</LOCATION>, 2,467,845, up from 2,364,000.
   _<LOCATION>Maryland</LOCATION>, 4,732,934, up from 4,217,000.
   _<LOCATION>Nevada</LOCATION>, 1,193,287, up from 800,000.
   _<LOCATION>North Carolina</LOCATION>, 6,552,927, up from 5,882,000.
   _<LOCATION>Ohio</LOCATION>, 10,777,514, down from 10,798,000.
   _<LOCATION>Virginia</LOCATION>, 6,127,680, up from 5,347,000.
   _<LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION>, 4,826,675, up from 4,132,000.
</TEXT>
