<HEAD>Preliminary Census Figures Dismay Many Local Officials</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   From the great cities to the small towns,
<LOCATION>America</LOCATION>'s municipalities are telling the federal government they
can't possibly be as small as census takers say.
   By the thousands, local officials are demanding something be
done about the <DATE>1990</DATE> Census. Even states are contesting the
preliminary figures, aware that the more residents they are
credited with, the more federal aid they will get and the greater
their representation in <ORGANIZATION>Congress</ORGANIZATION> will be.
   Some voices from the nationwide chorus:
   -``Unadulterated nonsense ... statistical grand larceny,'' said
<LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON>David N. Dinkins</PERSON>.
   -``There are errors everywhere,'' said <LOCATION>Detroit</LOCATION> research director
<ORGANIZATION>Juliette Okotie-Eboh</ORGANIZATION>.
   -``It really stretches credibility to the breaking point,'' said
<LOCATION>Hartford</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Conn.</LOCATION>, Mayor <PERSON>Carrie Saxon Perry</PERSON>.
   -``They missed our farthest south street,'' said <PERSON>Hays</PERSON>, <LOCATION>Iowa</LOCATION>,
<LOCATION>City</LOCATION> Clerk <PERSON>Judy Grothe</PERSON>.
   All were reacting to the preliminary results of the <ORGANIZATION>Census
Bureau</ORGANIZATION>'s <DATE>April 15</DATE> head count.
   The preliminary reports were sent out in late <DATE>August</DATE> and early
this month to give officials a chance to file challenges in time
for the bureau to double-check its numbers before announcing its
final count <DATE>Dec. 31</DATE>.
   Census Director <PERSON>Barbara Everitt Bryant</PERSON> has already told <ORGANIZATION>Congress</ORGANIZATION>
there will be big changes in the initial numbers.
   ``The census count will increase in practically every
jurisdiction throughout the country because of ongoing coverage
improvement programs,'' she said.
   Even some states that posted gains in the preliminary figures
are upset.
   Take <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION>. Despite recording significantly more people, state
officials say the count is not high enough.
   ``Our conservative estimate puts the state's population at about
17 million. If the census' final count ... stays with 16.8 million,
<LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION> will definitely be shortchanged,'' state Comptroller <PERSON>Bob
Bullock</PERSON> said.
   But it is clearly from the jurisdictions that showed losses that
the loudest complaints are coming.
   Such as <LOCATION>West Virginia</LOCATION>, credited with the largest population drop
of any state.
   ``Many West Virginians live up dirt roads and hollows, and
proving their existence has been as difficult as it has been for
the Census Bureau to find them,'' said <PERSON>Bob Brunner</PERSON>, spokesman for
Gov. <PERSON>Gaston Caperton</PERSON>.
   Or <LOCATION>Pennsylvania</LOCATION>, where <PERSON>Vincent Carocci</PERSON>, spokesman for
<LOCATION>Pennsylvania</LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON>Robert P. Casey</PERSON>, said the preliminary count
underestimated the population by 200,000 to 300,000. Census takers
undercounted the state's cities, <PERSON>Carocci</PERSON> said, because people there
are ``just harder to count.''
   Or tiny <LOCATION>Jacksonburg</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Ohio</LOCATION>, which the <ORGANIZATION>Census Bureau</ORGANIZATION> said has 14
residents. Last week, 39 Jacksonburg residents appeared at a
protest of the count. Between them, they said they could count at
least 26 more people in the town.
   Denver Mayor <PERSON>Federico Pena</PERSON> was ``stunned.'' <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON>Mario
Cuomo</PERSON> exclaimed, ``I don't believe it.'' <LOCATION>Atlanta</LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON>Maynard
Jackson</PERSON> said if errors aren't corrected, ``we'll see them in
court.''
   Barraged with such complaints, the <ORGANIZATION>Census Bureau</ORGANIZATION> is having
workers do rechecks of some neighborhoods, add late reports and
factor in military personnel overseas.
   The bureau has its hands full.
   In <LOCATION>Iowa</LOCATION>, officials say as many as 75,000 residents were missed.
   In <LOCATION>Louisiana</LOCATION>, said a representative of Avoyelles Parish, ``We
know for sure that's not right. Several types of errors were made
but I don't know what kind. ``Something went wrong, but I guarantee
that we will get to the bottom of this.''
   Why are the numbers so important?
   Simple. After the nation's population is counted every 10 years,
the <ORGANIZATION>House of Representatives</ORGANIZATION> is reapportioned and federal and state
aid formulas are adjusted. Losing people, or not growing as fast as
other places, can mean a loss of political power and federal aid
until the next census.
   The census news wasn't bad everywhere, though.
   <LOCATION>Seattle</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION> state officials are pleased with the
preliminary counts, which exceeded their own estimates.
   ``We still think there are people out there that the census did
not count, but generally we think they did a pretty good job,''
said urban research analyst <PERSON>Eric Friedli</PERSON>.
   ``My impression is that we have a smaller proportion of people
who aren't going to respond or who aren't going to be counted. I
don't see any outstanding reason to say this is a bad census,''
said <PERSON>Lawrence Weisser</PERSON>, a state research investigator.
   Officials in <LOCATION>Sacramento</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Calif.</LOCATION>, are puzzled by preliminary
census figures <PERCENT>5 percent</PERCENT> higher than they had estimated. ``I'm at a
loss,'' said <PERSON>Scott Mende</PERSON>, a city planner.
</TEXT>
