<LP>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. -- Kansas City elected its first black
mayor, Emanuel Cleaver.
   Mr. Cleaver, a minister and three-term city councilman,
won by a 53% to 47% margin in the nonpartisan contest with
fellow councilman Bob Lewellen. The city's population is
about 70% white.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The election received national attention this year when a
group of top business leaders passed over both men to back
their own candidate for mayor. That candidate, <PERSON>Brice Harris</PERSON>,
was eliminated in the <DATE>Feb. 26</DATE> primary. Some leading members
of the business group then switched to <PERSON>Mr. Cleaver</PERSON>, who
campaigned on a theme of economic development.
</TEXT>
