<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The partisan makeup of the <ORGANIZATION>House</ORGANIZATION> for the next
decade rests largely with voters in a dozen states this year. As
they choose governors and state legislators, these voters will be
picking the power brokers for major redistricting battles.
   The arcane redistricting process draws little attention from
voters. But national political parties are pouring <MONEY>millions of
dollars</MONEY> and advice into state legislative races that often are
ignored in <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION> except in years ending in zero.
   Redistricting occurs once a decade after the <ORGANIZATION>Census Bureau</ORGANIZATION>
completes its decennial head count. The population figures are used
to redistribute <ORGANIZATION>U.S. House</ORGANIZATION> seats among the 50 states and to redraw
congressional district lines.
   Some 19 <ORGANIZATION>House</ORGANIZATION> seats are expected to shift as a result of the
<DATE>1990</DATE> Census. Most of them will move from the Democratic-leaning
<ORGANIZATION>Northeast</ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION>Midwest</LOCATION> to the more conservative South and West,
where Republicans have enjoyed success in congressional and
presidential elections but lag behind Democrats at the state level.
   Democrats enter the redistricting process with a decided edge
and hope gains this year will serve as a springboard to <DATE>1992</DATE>, when
the party will try again to wrest control of the <ORGANIZATION>White House</ORGANIZATION> from
the <ORGANIZATION>GOP</ORGANIZATION>.
   Republicans for most of the <DATE>1980s</DATE> touted their ``1991 Plan'' as
the means of escaping their nearly 40 years as minority party in
the <ORGANIZATION>House</ORGANIZATION>. But the <ORGANIZATION>GOP</ORGANIZATION> now finds itself scrambling to defend its
major redistricting power bases against formidable Democratic
challenges.
   Already, the <ORGANIZATION>GOP</ORGANIZATION> is threatening to press legal challenges to
partisan plans it expects the Democrats to craft.
   ``We're in position this year to successfully defend most if not
all of our redistricting strengths and then peel off a few if not
more from the Republicans,'' said <PERSON>Tim Dickson</PERSON>, executive director
of the <ORGANIZATION>Democratic Party</ORGANIZATION>'s redistricting arm, Project 500.
   At stake is nothing less than control of the <ORGANIZATION>House</ORGANIZATION> through the
year <DATE>2003</DATE>; even modest Democratic gains would cement Republicans as
the minority party for the foreseeable future.
   Party operatives say new computer analyses that mix Census
demographics with voting records will allow anyone with a monopoly
on redistricting to fashion no-lose districts.
   ``You can slice up a state and preordain the results with
incredible accuracy,'' said <PERSON>Ben Ginsberg</PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION>Republican National
Committee</ORGANIZATION>'s chief counsel.
   The Republicans hoped for big gains after 17 seats shifted from
the Frost Belt to the Sun Belt after the <DATE>1980</DATE> Census. But Democrats
controlled much of the map drawing and ended up with a net gain of
three seats.
   The shifting is called reapportionment, the <ORGANIZATION>Census Bureau</ORGANIZATION> term
for deciding how many of the 435 <ORGANIZATION>House</ORGANIZATION> seats go to each state. Once
that's done the states - in most cases their legislatures - take on
the task of redistricting, literally redrawing the lines of each
congressional district.
   There are 6,144 legislative seats up for election in 46 states.
There are no legislative races this year in <LOCATION>Virginia</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>New Jersey</LOCATION>,
<LOCATION>Mississippi</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Kentucky</LOCATION>.
   After years of exhaustive research, the parties have narrowed
their targets to a handful to a dozen races in each of the major
redistricting battlegrounds - primarily states that are gaining or
losing seats.
   Fourteen of the shifting seats - and their accompanying
electoral votes in presidential elections - will be gobbled up by
<LOCATION>California</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Florida</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION>.
   In those states, Republicans now control the governor's office
but face stiff challenges this year.
   At the legislative level in those states, only control of the
<ORGANIZATION>Florida Senate</ORGANIZATION> appears in question; Democrats enjoy sizeable
advantages in both chambers of the <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>California</LOCATION>
legislatures and in the <ORGANIZATION>Florida House</ORGANIZATION>.
   Republicans are mounting an aggressive effort to pick up the
four seats they need to control the <ORGANIZATION>Florida Senate</ORGANIZATION>, which would
give the GOP a voice in redistricting should Republican Gov. <PERSON>Bob
Martinez</PERSON> lose his re-election bid.
   Democrats are cautiously optimistic they will retain their edge.
   The fight in the state destined to be the biggest redistricting
loser, <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>, focuses on the state <ORGANIZATION>Senate</ORGANIZATION>, where Democrats need
a net gain of four seats to win a monopoly on redistricting.
   ``If that happens what you will see is blatant political
gerrymandering,'' said the <ORGANIZATION>RNC</ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON>Ginsberg</PERSON>.
   He won't get an argument from Democrats on that point.
   ``The process is inherently political,'' said <ORGANIZATION>Democratic
National Committee</ORGANIZATION> redistricting guru <PERSON>Mark Bohannon</PERSON>. ``It was
designed that way, to benefit winners.''
   President <PERSON>Bush</PERSON> has visited <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> to help the <ORGANIZATION>GOP</ORGANIZATION>'s state
<ORGANIZATION>Senate</ORGANIZATION> effort, and Gov. <PERSON>Mario Cuomo</PERSON> is working hard for the
Democrats. <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> likely will lose three of its 34 <ORGANIZATION>House</ORGANIZATION> seats.
   Democrats also are spending heavily in hopes of gaining
redistricting monopolies in <LOCATION>Pennsylvania</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Indiana</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Michigan</LOCATION>.
They hope to capture the senates in <LOCATION>Pennsylvania</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Michigan</LOCATION> and
both chambers in <LOCATION>Indiana</LOCATION>, where the <ORGANIZATION>GOP</ORGANIZATION> has two-seat majorities in
the <ORGANIZATION>House</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Senate</ORGANIZATION>. With the <LOCATION>Ohio</LOCATION> gubernatorial contest leaning
Republican, Democrats also are targeting the <ORGANIZATION>Ohio Senate</ORGANIZATION>, where
they need a gain of three seats to win total control of the state
legislature.
   The party has realistic shots at those goals but faces uphill
odds in trying to erase slim <ORGANIZATION>GOP</ORGANIZATION> majorities in both chambers of the
<LOCATION>Arizona</LOCATION> legislature and the <ORGANIZATION>Colorado House</ORGANIZATION>.
   Democrats find themselves playing defense in the <LOCATION>Florida Senate</LOCATION>
contests as well as in <LOCATION>Illinois</LOCATION>, where Republicans need to gain two
seats to capture the <ORGANIZATION>Senate</ORGANIZATION>. Republicans also are trying to take
over the lower chambers in <LOCATION>Pennsylvania</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Oregon</LOCATION>, needing a gain
of three seats in each state.
   The <LOCATION>Pennsylvania</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Michigan</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Illinois</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Ohio</LOCATION> contests are
particularly important because each of these states is likely to
lose two congressional seats. Control over redistricting will
decide which incumbents get squeezed.
   The other likely losers are <LOCATION>Massachusetts</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>New Jersey</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>West
Virginia</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Kentucky</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Iowa</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Louisiana</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Kansas</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Montana</LOCATION>. Those
eight states will lose one seat each, according to preliminary
Census data.
   The redistricting winners are led by <LOCATION>California</LOCATION>, which should
gain seven seats and see its <ORGANIZATION>House</ORGANIZATION> delegation grow to 52. <LOCATION>Florida</LOCATION>'s
expected gain of four would bring its <ORGANIZATION>House</ORGANIZATION> delegation to 23. The
likely pickup of three seats by <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION> would swell its
representation in the <ORGANIZATION>House</ORGANIZATION> to 30.
   Together, these states would supply <PERCENT>24 percent</PERCENT> of <ORGANIZATION>House</ORGANIZATION> members
and hold 105 <ORGANIZATION>Electoral College</ORGANIZATION> votes - <PERCENT>38 percent</PERCENT> of the 270 needed
to win the <ORGANIZATION>White House</ORGANIZATION>.
   The other gainers, expected to pick up one seat each, likely
will be <LOCATION>Virginia</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>North Carolina</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Georgia</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Arizona</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION>.
   Heading into the elections there were just four states - <LOCATION>Idaho</LOCATION>,
<LOCATION>Kansas</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>New Hampshire</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>South Dakota</LOCATION> - in which Republicans have
outright control over state government and none of them are
considered major redistricting battlegrounds.
   Democrats, on the other hand, hold the governor's office and
control both legislative chambers in 15 states and at least two of
the three seats at the redistricting table in 23 others.
</TEXT>
